#Text=Cold as ice :
#Text=Wikinews interviews Marymegan
#Text=Daly on unusual new sea anemone
#Text=Tuesday , January 21 , 2014
#Text=In late 2010 a geological expedition to Antarctica drilled through the Ross Ice Shelf so they could send an ROV under it .
#Text=What they found was unexpected : Sea anemones .
#Text=In their thousands they were doing what no other species of sea anemone is known to do — they were living in the ice itself .
#Text=Edwardsiella andrillae and its habitat Image : Daly et al.

#Text=Discovered by the ANDRILL [ Antarctic Drilling ] project , the team was so unprepared for biological discoveries they did not have suitable preservatives and the only chemicals available obliterated the creature 's DNA .
#Text=Nonetheless Marymegan Daly of Ohio State University confirmed the animals were a new species .
#Text=Named Edwardsiella andrillae after the drilling project that found it , the anemone was finally described in a PLOS ONE paper last month .
#Text=ANDRILL lowered their cylindrical camera ROV down a freshly-bored 270 m ( 890 ft ) hole , enabling it to reach seawater below the ice .
#Text=The device was merely being tested ahead of its planned mission retrieving data on ocean currents and the sub-ice environment .

#Text=Instead it found what ANDRILL director Frank Rack of the University of Nebraska – Lincoln , a co-author of the paper describing the find , called the " total serendipity " of " a whole new ecosystem that no one had ever seen before " .

column1: #Text=The discovery raises many questions .
#Text=Burrowing sea anemones worm their way into substrates or use their tentacles to dig , but it 's unclear how E. andrillae enters the hard ice .

#Text=With only their tentacles protruding into the water from the underneath of the ice shelf questions also revolve around how the animals avoid freezing , how they reproduce , and how they cope with the continuously melting nature of their home .
#Text=Their diet is also a mystery .
#Text=What fascinates me about sea anemones is that they 're able to do things that seem impossible — Marymegan Daly
#Text=E. andrillae is an opaque white , with an inner ring of eight tentacles and twelve-to-sixteen tentacles in an outer ring .
#Text=The ROV 's lights produced an orange glow from the creatures , although this may be produced by their food .
#Text=It measures 16 – 20mm ( 0.6 – 0.8in ) but when fully relaxed can extend to triple that .
#Text=Genetic analysis being impossible , Daly turned to dissection of the specimens but could find nothing out of the ordinary .
#Text=Scientists hope to send a biological mission to explore the area under the massive ice sheet , which is in excess of 600 miles ( 970km ) wide .

#Text=The cameras also observed worms , fish that swim inverted as if the icy roof was the sea floor , crustaceans and a cylindrical creature that used appendages on its ends to move and to grab hold of the anemones .
#Text=NASA is providing funding to aid further research , owing to possible similarities between this icy realm and Europa , a moon of Jupiter .
#Text=Biological research is planned for 2015 .
#Text=An application for funding to the U.S. National Science Foundation , which funds ANDRILL , is also pending .
